body:
We don't do much around selecting devices so it's unexpected there would be an error about the current set of devices not being valid.

Can you share how you're creating the InferenceSession? Are you setting any flags when adding the NNAPI execution provider?

Is there any other output around that error string that may provide further info?

Is it possible to run with verbose logging turned on to see if there's anything helpful in that? Set the [session log level](https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/api/java/ai/onnxruntime/OrtSession.SessionOptions.html#setSessionLogLevel(ai.onnxruntime.OrtLoggingLevel)) to ORT_LOGGING_LEVEL_VERBOSE.

I create the session in the following way:
```java
suspend fun getModel(modelID: Int): ByteArray = withContext(Dispatchers.IO) {
        return@withContext context.resources.openRawResource(modelID).readBytes()
    }
   val sessionOptions = OrtSession.SessionOptions()
            sessionOptions.setSessionLogLevel(OrtLoggingLevel.ORT_LOGGING_LEVEL_VERBOSE)
            sessionOptions.addNnapi(
                    EnumSet.of(
                        NNAPIFlags.CPU_DISABLED,
                        NNAPIFlags.USE_FP16,
                    )
                )
            ortSession = ortEnv.createSession(
                getModel(
                    context.resources.getIdentifier(
                        modelFile,
                        "raw",
                        context.packageName
                    )
                ), sessionOptions
            )`
```
On a Samsung, there is no crash, but NNAPIs are way slower than Cpu (7sec vs 1sec), and there is no much difference in setting NNAPIFlags.CPU_ONLY.

FWIW even if it wasn't failing the model is not going to run well using NNAPI due to a number of operators that are not currently supported. See all the output with `Node supported: [0]` in them. That will mean the model is broken into lots of partitions, and switching between a partition that can run on NNAPI and a partition that has to use the CPU EP will be more costly than simply running using the CPU EP.

Does it fail if you do not specify CPU_DISABLED? I suspect there's an operator we attempt to use NNAPI for, but the hardware vendor hasn't implemented it. The NNAPI internals are attempting to use the reference CPU implementation (which is generally horribly slow with no optimizations) but the CPU_DISABLED flag means that device is not available. We run that check [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/adbc0757ad9f96f8b44d3de526c36917ab6e4431/onnxruntime/core/providers/nnapi/nnapi_builtin/builders/model_builder.cc#L593-L595)

If that is the case, that's 2 separate reasons why using NNAPI is not going to perform well on this device and the default CPU EP is going to be a better option.

Thanks for the info, I've read of the problems of switching between NNAPIs and CPU EP; my main focus is to conduct experiments, not having the best execution times.
If I do not specify anything, it does not crash as I think it starts running using NNAPIs CPU (~7sec, using no NNAPIs is ~1.5sec). 
The things that I would like to understand better are:
- if an operator is not supported, why is the app crashing? Shouldn't it fallback on the ONNX Cpu EP? 
- why by using a Samsung S9, I can use NNAPIs with CPU_DISABLED, but the execution times are always ~7sec, same as using CPU_ONLY?
from what I see, it seems that even if many operators are supported by NNAPIs acceleration they are not actually run on accelerators. Even if there was switching between CPU EP and NNAPIs acceleration, I would expect inference time to be higher or lower, not always exactly the same.

> * if an operator is not supported, why is the app crashing? Shouldn't it fallback on the ONNX Cpu EP?

It potentially could, but that may create a more mysterious performance issue vs. the current hard failure where the user is forced to make a different choice. 

> * why by using a Samsung S9, I can use NNAPIs with CPU_DISABLED, but the execution times are always ~7sec, same as using CPU_ONLY?

Performance will be significantly impacted by the unsupported operators causing it to use the CPU EP. Currently the NNAPI EP does not have the logic to convert ConvTranspose, ScatterND, or GridSample to an NNAPI equivalent. There are also some Resize nodes where the input shape isn't known causing those to not be handled. That applies to all devices.

This is different to attempting to use NNAPI for a supported operator but finding the hardware vendor has not implemented a non-CPU version of the operator. The Samsumg S9 doesn't have this issue, but that is orthogonal to the lack of handling for ConvTranspose etc.

>   from what I see, it seems that even if many operators are supported by NNAPIs acceleration they are not actually run on accelerators. Even if there was switching between CPU EP and NNAPIs acceleration, I would expect inference time to be higher or lower, not always exactly the same.

The log output would show what it is running using NNAPI. Note that the CPU_ONLY flag for the NNAPI EP will mean the NNAPI model we create for the supported nodes will be run by NNAPI using CPU. i.e. CPU_ONLY does not mean run everything using the CPU EP. 

What execution time do you get if you do not use NNAPI at all? i.e. do not add the NNAPI EP to the inference session.

**Description**: 
Changes in opsets 16 and 17 don't require any updates to currently supported NNAPI/Coreml operator+type combinations.

**Motivation and Context**
#12793  involved an opset 16 model with PRelu. There were other issues, but the PRelu should at least have been able to be handled.
